'''Abu Salih Mansur''' (died 915) was a [[Samanid]] prince, who served as governor during the reign of his uncle [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad]], his cousin [[Ahmad Samani]], and [[Nasr II]].

== Biography ==
Abu Salih governed several provinces during the reign of Isma'il ibn Ahmad and Ahmad Samani. The first time he is mentioned as a governor is in 902 when he was appointed as governor of [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] by Isma'il ibn Ahmad who had conquered territory as far as [[Qazvin]] in Iran. During his governorship of Ray, he became friend with [[Muhammad ibn Zakariya al-Razi]],<ref name="iranicaonline.org"/> a famous [[Persian people|Persian]] scholar. In 910, or 911, he was appointed as governor of [[Sistan]] by Ahmad Samani. However, Abu Salih's oppressive taxation policies sparked a revolt in Sistan within in 912, led by the [[Kharijites|Khariji]] [[Muhammad ibn Hurmuz]], who was a supporter of the [[Saffarid]] [[Amr ibn Ya'qub]]. Abu Salih was then taken prisoner until the rebellion was crushed by a Samanid army under Husain ibn 'Ali Marvarrudhi in 913.<ref name="iranicaonline.org">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/abu-saleh-mansur-b ''ABŪ ṢĀLEḤ MANṢŪR'', C. E. Bosworth, '''Encyclopaedia Iranica''']</ref> 'Amr was sent to [[Samarkand]], while the other rebel leaders were killed. [[Simjur al-Dawati]] then replaced Mansur as governor of Sistan.

In 914, Mansur was appointed governor of Khorasan, but anarchy unleashed by the death of Ahmad ibn Ismail and the ascent to the throne of the 8 year old child [[Nasr II]]. Mansur's father, [[Ishaq ibn Ahmad]], revolted at [[Samarkand]], while Mansur proclaimed himself as [[Emir]] of [[Nishapur]], and several other cities.
He died a natural death in Nishapur probably in 915, before an army sent against him led by Hammuya ibn Ali reached the city.<ref>''The Samanids'', R.N. Frye, '''The Cambridge History of Iran''', 141.</ref>

