{{Infobox NRHP | name = Leive, Parks and Stapp Opera House | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes | image = Leive, Parks and Stapp Opera House.jpg | caption = Leive, Parks and Stapp Opera House, November 2012 | location= 321-325 Second St., [[Aurora, Indiana]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|3|23|N|84|54|4|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Indiana#USA | built = {{Start date|1878}} | architect = Lindsay, Thomas | architecture = Italianate | added = September 20, 1994 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 94001120<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} '''Leive, Parks and Stapp Opera House''', also known as the Grand Opera House, is a historic [[opera house]] located at [[Aurora, Indiana|Aurora]], [[Dearborn County, Indiana]]. It was built in 1878, and is a three-story, [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] style brick building. It measures 53 feet wide and 104 feet deep. The front facade features a cast iron storefront with [[pilaster]]s with [[Corinthian order]] capitals.<ref name="SHAARD">{{cite web| url = https://secure.in.gov/apps/dnr/shaard/welcome.html| title = Indiana State Historic Architectural and Archaeological Research Database (SHAARD) | publisher = Department of Natural Resources, Division of Historic Preservation and Archaeology | format = Searchable database| accessdate = 2015-08-01}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web| url = https://secure.in.gov/apps/dnr/shaard/r/214d7/N/Leive_Parks_and_Stapp_Opera_House_Dearborn_CO_Nom.pdf| title = National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination Form: Leive, Parks and Stapp Opera House | accessdate = 2015-09-01| author =Jeffrey L. Huntington| format = PDF| date=February 1993}} and Accompanying photographs.</ref>{{rp|5}}
It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1994.<ref name="nris"/> It is located in the [[Downtown Aurora Historic District]].
