[[File:Mesto Brno - Mahenovo divadlo 2.jpg|right|thumb|Mahen Theatre]] <!-- [[File:Brno 9772.jpg|right|thumb|Janáček Theatre]] [[File:Brno - Reduta theatre.jpg|right|thumb|Reduta Theatre]] --> The '''National Theatre Brno''' ({{lang-cs|'''Národní divadlo Brno'''}}) is the major [[theater (structure)|theatre house]] in [[Brno]]. It was established in 1884 and modeled on the [[National Theatre (Prague)|National Theatre in Prague]].
It now consists of three [[stage (theatre)|stages]]: * [[Mahen Theatre]] (drama), originally the German-language ''Theatre on the Walls'' (construction finished in 1882), the first theatre building on [[Continental Europe|the continent]] with electric lighting (designed by [[Thomas Alva Edison]] himself). * [[Janáček Theatre]] (opera, ballet), a modern building from 1961–1965. Zdenĕk Neverla was appointed general director of the Janáček Opera House in 1990.<ref>News item in ''[[Opera (magazine)|Opera]]'', March 1990, p291.</ref> * [[Reduta Theatre]], the oldest theatre house in [[Central Europe]], recently reconstructed. In December 1767 the twelve-year-old [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] gave a concert there.
